-- Proof by Analogy
--
-- Classical: Not a formal proof technique (informal heuristic)
-- CredTT: Low-credence morphism with visible weakness
--
-- Example: "This proof should work like the other one"
-- Classical: Not a proof, just intuition
-- CredTT: Morphism @ c with c < 1 (explicitly weak)

-- Classical logic has no place for analogical reasoning
-- It's either a proof (true) or not (unknown)

-- CredTT can express WEAK analogies:
-- "A is like B" @ 0.7
-- The morphism exists but is uncertain

-- Analogy: similar structure
postulate structure_similar : A_like_B @ 7/10

-- Transfer: if P(A) and A ~ B, then probably P(B)
postulate P_of_A : P_holds_for_A @ 1

-- Analogical transfer: 1 * 0.7 = 0.7
-- "P probably holds for B" @ 0.7

-- This is HONEST analogical reasoning:
-- The weakness of the analogy is VISIBLE
-- The transferred conclusion is appropriately weakened

-- Chain of analogies:
-- A ~ B @ 0.9
-- B ~ C @ 0.8
-- A ~ C @ 0.9 * 0.8 = 0.72

-- Analogies compose but DEGRADE
-- Each step of analogical reasoning weakens confidence

-- Why this matters:
-- Scientific reasoning often uses analogy
-- "This drug worked for mice, probably works for humans"
-- Analogy @ c, result @ c

-- Mathematical analogy:
-- "Proof for R^2 should generalize to R^n"
-- Analogy @ 0.95 (pretty confident it works)
-- Need to actually check to get @ 1

-- CredTT makes analogy a FIRST-CLASS citizen
-- Not "informal heuristic" but "low-credence proof"
-- The credence explicitly tracks confidence

-- Stability of analogy:
-- Low-credence analogy is Interior (not Stable1)
-- Transferred claims inherit this Interior status
